ion=\"Fantasmes&#39; &quot;Sidetracked&quot; (Digital Download)\"]<a href=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/fantasmes.jpg\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-73\" title=\"fantasmes\" src=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/fantasmes-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nThis is then where digital downloads overtake: skimming printing and packaging prices (also having the best of both worlds still preserving all the art from its counterpart) and putting their product in the information superhighway almost guaranteeing a solid listen to anyone with internet access (granted they know how to use it, apologies to “The Jersey Shore” cast.). 2010 saw the marvelous, and digital-only, releases of Fantasmes (“Sidtracked”) and Similar ( self-titled EP)which demonstrates how some are taking advantage of the ever-evolving contemporary communications. Yet a modern reaction to the excess of accessibility is skepticism: problems with “quality control” (any band could upload their rattle and hum) and the sometimes the deviation into shoddy artwork and assembly. The main difficulty is that local releases have limited their digital packaging to rudimentary aspects such as cover sleeve and maybe lyrics and have yet to expand features (much like Radiohead did their 2009 free downloadable single “These AreMy Twisted Words” which incorporated fascinating ASCII art panels among other tidbits.) One should not decry that bands with digital releases are merely partaking in shabby productions, these groups are merely accommodating to the times.\r\n\r\nBut at the gist of it, since audio quality is a creative and economic control which the band is solely responsible for, concrete format holds scissor that will the unmake the Gordian knot. The metaphysics of the experience are fundamental for appreciation: the act of unwrapping, popping it in and listening are held by the narrative structure of creating an immersive experience that  is a dialectic between the listener, the object of aesthetic knowledge which  is the “real” record (whether it be 12’’ or 12 cm) , and the band itself, something which doesn’t necessarily translate to listening music on the go (iPod or in a car) or engaging it mechanically via a person to computer listening session (not “dissing” this experience of course.)\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_77\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"150\" caption=\"Similar EP (Digital Download) \"]<a href=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/similar.jpg\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-77 \" title=\"similar\" src=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/similar-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nIt would be interesting to see a more inclusive and expansive record/data experience, such as online exclusive added bonuses á la Director’s Cut,  beside the digital download bonus option which is a staple for both CD and vinyl releases nowadays (the 7’’ “Spooky Fools” being one of those). Though concrete format seems to be going down in sales (thanks to internet piracy which none of us listeners partake, ahem) and everything now is digested in itty-bitty data fun-sized chunks, people will probably continue getting their literal hands on their favorite tracks for a while. The times have certainly changed (as well as the rules of the game) it’s reassuring that there are still dedicated enough aural art devotees hanging around, and they are making it their task that music gets out, ensuring that people have options like they deserve to.','Local music\'s contemporary conundrum: digital vs. physical format. ','','inherit','open','open','','72-revision-16','','','2011-02-12 18:19:19','2011-02-12 18:19:19','',72,'http://modernaddendum.com/2011/02/72-revision-16/',0,'revision','',0),(119,1,'2011-02-24 10:55:25','2011-02-24 10:55:25','Dandy, deacadent, bon vivant or bouffant, Enrique Olivares the II, Esq.  possesses