such a fashion that they have been rewarded with annual scholarships at Berklee from 16,000$ ranging up to a full tuition.\r\n\r\nIt is not difficult to see why these up-and-comers are scrounging up such moolah: from the get go, the dexterity and skill is evident. The first flight of students was a vocal ensemble led by Professor Darcel Wilson which blew the audience away with their clamorous pipes and soaring chorus. The second flight gravitated away from vocalizing and into the instrumental. Led by instructor Oscar Stagnaro, the performance veered into a fusion pomp that not only included jazz staples such as upright bass, drums and piano, but also featured electric guitar and violin phrasing. The third presentation reminisced with big band style that featured a giant brass section, led by Bob Pilkington and segued into the finale with a Latin jazz blowup featuring all of the students. With clouds amassing, but still slightly sunny, it was fascinating to watch local talent have a very tactful grasp of musical forms such as fusion and big band and stringed instruments that are somewhat alien to the island’s orchestration and taste.\r\n\r\nAs interesting as the summer workshop proved to be, nothing could prepare everyone for the follow-up act. Ninety Miles is a collaboration between Grammy-award winning musicians vibist Stefon Harris, trumpet player Christian Scott and our very own saxophonist David Sánchez. Meeting and recording in Havana in 2010, the group will be releasing their self-titled album in a month on Concord records, a production that is being hyped as probably be the biggest jazz recording of the year. It was the group’s debut performance, and the audience was luck enough to be regaled with their music and performance.\r\n\r\nHarris initiated the show with a jagged vibraphone melody that was backed up by drummer and native Henry Cole and bassist Luques Curtis with an ultra-tight driving punch but suddenly turned into phrasing madness once Scott and Sánchez doubled the melodic motif and lead into ravenous improvisation. Performers at heart, the bandleaders juggled soloing duties but also limelighted pianist Luis Perdomo’s light-fingered touch and counter-pointed sense of harmony as well as percussionist Eddy Mauricio Herrera’s hand drum rolls.\r\n\r\nNinety Miles is the distance between Cuba and Florida’s lowest-reaching point and the group’s music reflects the geographical and latitudinal qualities of the music: grounded in the Latin and Caribbean rhythms of Sánchez’s Sargasso Sea as well as the New Orleans spirit of which Harris and Scott hail from. Their music is forceful yet mollified by the mystic and chiming euphony of Harris’ vibraphone and the wind section is anchored in long phrasing. With influences raging from Davis to Zappa, the ensemble also grooved with the dream-like with their composition “Los Olividados” (“The Forgotten”), an in memoriam for those wrecked by Katrina and left awashed in the rain. Though the clouds stopped barking and started biting with swaths of rain, the band maintained focus, jovial and energetic throughout their set, rearranging instruments in the face of aqueous adversity.\r\n\r\nThe final set could only be mete with an explosive bang  and Humberto Ramírez and his appropriately named Big Band indeed did provide. The Yerba Buena house band has been serving up boogaloo with a side of jazz every Monday for the past 2 yours and orchestrated a tightwound tribute set dedicated to jazz legends Tito Puente and timbalero extraordinaire, singer and bandleader Tito Rodríguez, chanteuse La Lupe and ‘ol Blue Eyes himself, Frank Sinatra. The rambunctious ensemble cruised through Fania favorites such as Puente’s “Complicación” and Rodríguez’s “Avisale a mi contrario” sung by invitee Josué Rosado as well as tearjerkers and heartbreakers such as La Lupe’s “La tirana” as well as the saucier “Fever”, performed by Michelle Brava. Though Sinatra’s swing  might have seemed a bit at odds with mambo jazz, NJ singer Mike Ritacco graced numbers such as “I’ve Got You Under My Skin” and “My Way” fitted in nicely with the rest of the repertoire. With the frenetic beat, the audience could not but dance in the face of the ritualistic upheaval of the stage and the orchestra pushed the moment to its crisis with a tour de force rendition of Puente’s “Cuban Fantasy” with an encore of Sinatra’s “New York, New York” followed by spastic brass soloing and a wall of timbales-on-conga blasts set to Rodríguez’s “Mama Guela”\r\n\r\nThe Heineken JazzFest coalesced a series voices coming from different backgrounds: the Big Easy, the Big Apple, Havana and our own backyard and turned them into something palpable that it grabs you by the guts. The word eclectic gets thrown around much these days but pluralism is still pertinent in the island’s musical taste, and the festival sure did leave a good one at that. The night sky cleared up towards the end, just in time for when everyone realized that it the whole event as plainly speaking: it was great. For those who lived through Ninety Miles and all the great acts, and even those acts that didn’t play, it was memorable, energetic, amazing and all that jazz.','Heineken JazzFest Pt. 2','Ends not with a whimper, but with a bang. ','publish','open','open','','heineken-jazzfest-pt-2','','','2011-06-09 00:00:15','2011-06-09 00:00:15','',0,'http://modernaddendum.com/?p=210',0,'post','',0),(112,2,'2011-02-18 19:27:07','2011-02-18 19:27:07','','WWYVD?','','inherit','open','open','','yvltrs','','','2011-02-18 19:27:07','2011-02-18 19:27:07','',111,'http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/yvltrs.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(113,2,'2011-02-18 19:26:21','2011-02-18 19:26:21','People try to live safely: they avoid danger, hazards and any other misnomers that prone the body towards discombobulation. Fortunately, the two-man outfit Youvultures comes crashing, obliterating superstructures with their first release, the EP <em>WWYVD?</em>\n\nThe title tracks opens up with a mock fanfare before whipping out its machine-gun fuzzed-out bass slams and back breaking beats spread across everywhere. Seconds into the track it freezes with a choir yelps before resuming its rolling-thunder groove. The opener assures the doubtful, and probably frightened, listeners that the remaining rumpus does not shy away from this aesthetic: an ear-annihilating, relentless clusterfuck. “HYV” is an upward scaling distorted chromatic gear-shift drive-by with vacuum-sealed ultra-tight drumming before it begins collapsing on itself with a flood of modulated noises and half-time percussion extracted from a Mars landscape.\n\n“Carne Trémula’s” intro sound clip urges the listener to the proverbial past time of “fucking your own face” but the band opts to facilitate the process with this ripper before segueing into the pseudo-dance floor stomper “La Playa” , á la Les Rallizes Denudés ,which will force the limbs of brain-melted wasteoids into flux while the closer “La Porno” phases in and out with moaning-cum-feedback laden devastating sonic raunchiness.\n\nThe band juggles between hyper-constructed angular runs, inspired by their high-school algebra classes, and full-blown noise warbles. Youvultures might have The Locust-inspired presentation but their execution beckons to a wider audience.\n\nProduction is sleek and the duo set-up helps create a balance in equalization: drums don’t tread on the bass and the bass has enough mid-range punch to cut through production. The cornucopia of Moog-like soundscapes is not cluttered or muddied under the instruments and ring out with clarity and nefariousness.  The soundclip intros are an interesting addition, demonstrating craftsmanship in the record: it’s not just a loose amalgamation of singles and whatnot but more of a solid cultural artifact with a narrative that gives it cohesion.\n\nThe only discrepancy is the record’s length, clocking it at a little less than 10 minutes, something w