y as staunch defender Fred Astaire preserves relentlessly yet stylishly.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"></p>\r\nThough  the pocket square has long been associated as either an ornament upon  the upper axis of the male silhouette or a personalized gift to that  darling and effervescent sweetheart, it goes without saying that the  hanky also enjoyed a long tradition of practical usage. During the  Renaissance, men considered wiping mouth with their sleeves boorish  (poor cuffs!) and opted for the cloth and the 18th century with its  introduction of the snuff box and frequently sneezing flops secured its  place in the male’s attire. But this accessory wasn’t promoted from  booger blunder duty to ornamental embellishment until the First World  War when British uniform back pockets were sewn so tightly that the  handkerchief had to migrate to the looser fitting breast pocket. The  slightly disgusting sight of a used cloth\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_135\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"235\" caption=\"Bitches be loving hankies. \"]<a href=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/Wolfe.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-135\" title=\"Wolfe\" src=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/Wolfe.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"235\" height=\"235\" /></a></dt> </dl></div>\r\ndangling on a corporal’s chest  provoked utter disdain for such a portrait and the one for blowin’  promptly switched places with the one for showin’. The swapping settled  things once and for all: the handkerchief is meant to exalt the male  figure, and how!\r\n\r\nThe  pocket square has many a work in its line of duty including  complementing and harmonizing the complete aesthetic (the breast pockets  are stitched in the jacket for a reason gents) ethos but these process  also have some petite rules. Example: here is writer Tom Wolfe\'s patterned which hanky marries his checked shirt with a solid tie with grace and aplomb. For one, the square should  aim to echo one of the colors gracing either the shirt or the tie.  Matching a tie with a handkerchief proves to be too overwhelming and  amateurish in presentation (remember gentlemen, we are to strive to be a  living, breathing Caravaggio, not a Jackson Pollock.) If one is to add  an outside color the ensemble via the hanky, one should make sure it  does not overpower the main color. If one is to sport a navy blazer with  a white oxford button-down, a dark-hued hanky ties together the colors  while a gray suit met with a checked blue shirt encourages a livelier  companion for the stroll about town romp (patterned accessories go well  with solids while a solid pocket garment provides support for the more  daring main events.) Also, mix and match tie and square texture: a silk  tie should be accompanied by a dry   handkerchief (cotton or  foulard work exceptionally well)while thicker looking neckwear should go hand <a href=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/whimsey.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-151\" title=\"whimsey\" src=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/whimsey-222x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"222\" height=\"300\" /></a>in hand with a silken, or wet garment as does dandy Lord Breaulove Whimsy with a puffed green garment.\r\n\r\nThe  manifold possibilities of squares and peaks featured in the breast  pockets of past tall, dark and handsomes are a testament of how  individuals give their own personal twist to a long-standing classic.  Cary Grant irregularly angled his to give a little bite to his attire  while Fred Astaire puffed his to complement his entertainment pomp.  Though the thought of folding one’s own handkerchief might send men  scrounging for the hills, this seemingly daunting feat is actually quite  simple to accomplish. The internet provides illustrative guides to the  process while your local dapper dandy is more than willing to guide you  through the ordeal. The magic of folding and placing the handkerchief is  making sure it is not angular and mathematical (since it demonstrates  angularity and constriction) and that it points towards your shoulder and not inward. The biggest faux-pas a man could commit  would be to over-emphasize the hanky by making it bulbous and intrusive  for it detracts attention from the face and the attire. When purchasing a  handkerchief, make sure it does not bulge in the pocket (style sage  Alan Flusser suggests a range between 16 and 18 inch. Square).\r\n\r\nThe  handkerchief is not going anywhere as long as men with keen eyes for  reinventing a modern classic continue adapting the tradition into  contemporary times. The hanky adds layers of suaveness and  sophistication to the everyday code and as a true symbol of stylish  “savoir faire” and possesses the ability to transform any  business-formal enslaved man into a true mammal of paradise, which every  male should strive to embody through imagination.\r\n<div class=\"mceTemp mceIEcenter\"><dl id=\"attachment_152\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\" style=\"width: 310px;\"> <dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><a href=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/othello.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-152\" title=\"othello\" src=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/othello-300x234.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"234\" /></a>[/caption]','A Dandy\'s guide to: Handkerchiefs. ','','publish','open','open','','a-dandys-guide-to-handkerchiefs','','','2011-03-04 01:17:33','2011-03-04 01:17:33','',0,'http://modernaddendum.com/?p=134',0,'post','',0),(130,1,'2011-02-24 02:05:54','2011-02-24 02:05:54','<a id=\"set-post-thumbnail\" class=\"thickbox\" title=\"Set featured image\" href=\"media-upload.php?post_id=2&amp;type=image&amp;TB_iframe=1\"><img class=\"attachment-post-thumbnail alignleft\" title=\"166350_1532784688016_1486740030_1148254_6640674_n\" src=\"../wp-content/uploads/2011/01/166350_1532784688016_1486740030_1148254_6640674_n-400x400.jpg\" alt=\"166350_1532784688016_1486740030_1148254_6640674_n\" width=\"240\" height=\"240\" /></a>Dandy, deacadent, bon vivant or bouffant, Enrique Olivares the II, Esq.  possesses a B.A. in English and lives in Guaynabo. He doesn\'t know which is worse. He likes rock n\' roll and this humble servant has endeavored to meticulously write about it. He writes for a Puerto Rican newspaper titled the Daily Sun, concerning matters lofty, fashionable and artistic.  He also has a selection of lyrical poetry published in the magazines: <em>Tonguas</em>, <em>Hotel </em><em>Abismo</em> and <em>Bacanal </em>\r\n\r\nThe Modern Addendum is an amalgamation of rock n\' roll criticism and other tidbits deign of study.\r\n\r\nHe is currently dedicating his efforts to being the most elegant man this side of the Atlantic.\r\n\r\nHe is making some progress.','About','','inherit','open','open','','2-revision-5','','','2011-02-24 02:05:54','2011-02-24 02:05:54','',2,'http://modernaddendum.com/2011/02/2-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(133,2,'2011-02-24 02:14:55','2011-02-24 02:14:55','If one would pick up their nearest antonym dictionary and look up the word terrible, most likely you’d find yourself faced with Dávila 666’s latest foot-stomping reeling-and-a-rocking extravaganza “Tan Bajo” (“So Low”), officially released Tuesday on In the Red Records. Don’t be fooled by their name the band is synonymous with sultry sonic choruses and Stooges-like savage riffing, the band’s sophomore releases breaches out into disparate arenas to lay down a good ol’ slab of catchy, gritty garage rock n’ roll.\r\n\r\nThe record opens up with the self-titled track: the meandering singing of a drunken man suffocated in reverberated warble both pathetic and nostalgic. The record quickly segues in “Obsesionao” a hazy hothouse number carried on a driving bas- lick that kicks things into high gear once the verse ends and song detonates into one of the many infectious chorus that funnels into a skittering fuzz-laden guitar solo before pulling back to its original groove. This time around, as the track is a testament to, their Hispanic majesties have gorged down psych records (and other questionable chemicals) and given the record an electric cover of night which permeates every song with delectable echoes à la 13<sup>th</sup> Floor Elevators and dynamic modulations which zoom toward the cranial matter. Songs end abruptly, zoning out in reverse or collapsing on themselves creating a more expansive experience, tripping out on production effects. These orchestral psychedelic moves draw up on its other derivatives as well, such as the Jesus and Mary Chain in “Si me vez”, a melancholic ride hoisted up by a vortex of reverberation.\r\n\r\nNot only are they flirting with psychadelia in this gobbledygook but also with rhythm and blues in their sweaty skid row-cum-crossroads hustle “Los Cruce” complete with graveyard hound backup vocals. Tracks also harken back to the lost heyday of 50’s and 60’s bubblegum girl group gamut as the sextet pricks up ears and harangues them with the six-way whistles and Chiffons hums in songs like “Eso que me haces” and “Esa nena nunca regreso” that will blow up the dance-floor with these romper-stompers, shaking tambourines and behinds like tomorrow never comes. They also revive the slow-dancing, tear-jerker high school favorite form of the ballad with “Yo seria otro”, complete with madman Phil Spector-like violin chorus for all you leather-backed, leader of the pack heartbreakers, and “¡Diablo!”, telling the story of someone cuckolded by none-other than his own dastardly cousin. Just because the boys are picking up more 45’s from their pop predecessor, this doesn’t mean that they’ve lost all their bite. “Mala” is rapid-fire door-kicking punks squabble with furious down strumming guitars while “Patitas” will clench your eardrums with its thumps and wolf-whistles but crush ‘em with guitar squeals and thuds.\r\n\r\nLyrically, the album is a raunchy hodgepodge of late night rendez-vous in typical rock n’ roll fashion but this time, the band touches more eclectic themes at a more penetrating level. Love, especially its many obstacles, proves to be the underlying narrative of the record. Either too little, too late or too much, too soon it seems corrupted in everything done in this day and age. Physical relationships with out it, there are still traces of heartbreak and the album explores the fissures of it. On the flipside, “Robacuna” is a moronic ditty about a Lolita-seeker with ominous mobile clutter on the feedback, demonstrating the darker side of the band while “Ratata” is poignant mock of the ever-increasing crime subculture. For the sake of children and decorum, racier nuances found in the record are left out of this review.\r\n\r\nProduction wise, the grainy ambiance surrounding the album provides a rawer and more garage-ish sonic aura that complements the decadent psychdelia going on at the crazier seams of the album. Guitars crunch (the multiple solos in this album are a quite a doozy), bass booms, drums cut hold everything up and the howlin’ and screamin’ chants cut through the dense mix (it goes without saying that the inclusion of synths is a nice touch). The album also balances pretty well the rampant floods of effects inside the tracks with sobering moments where the multiple voices can ring out. The myriad of musicians help give the record a fuller wall-of-sound effect with counterpoint vocals employing sticky sing-a-longs throughout the experience. The only discrepancy with this type of aesthetic is that it might initially turn off more conservative listeners who might mistake the sound for a shoddy-recorded compilation of demos but in reality, the record is an extremely calculated shot.\r\n\r\n“Tan Bajo” is eclectic, electrifying, catch and most importantly fun. It goes without saying that the record is one of the most fascinating local cultural artifacts (with member monikers à la Ronettes such as Sir Charles, AJ, Panda and Gigi Davila as well as The Latin Snake and Jota Vigilante) out there combining the band’s love for U.S. blues, soul, bubblegum, psych and punk but inevitably infusing it with the street narrative of the island. Dávila 666 sound like Menudo with a criminal record and you’d be hard-pressed to not like this ripper of an album.','Dávila 666 goes garage trippin\' in \"Tan Bajo\"','','inherit','open','open','','125-revision-3','','','2011-02-24 02:14:55','2011-02-24 02:14:55','',125,'http://modernaddendum.com/2011/02/125-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(135,2,'2011-03-04 00:37:25','2011-03-04 00:37:25','','Wolfe','Writer Tom Wolfe\'s patterned hanky marries his checked shirt with a solid tie with grace and aplomb. ','inherit','open','open','','wolfe','','','2011-03-04 00:37:25','2011-03-04 00:37:25','',134,'http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/Wolfe.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(136,2,'2011-03-04 00:30:30','2011-03-04 00:30:30','In Shakespeare’s “Othello”, our very dear, and very Moorish, leading man  is  driven to suffocate the last beating breath out of his lover  Desdemona’s body because of a confusion over a token of affection he  gifted her, a handkerchief. It is incredible to think that such an  amourous detail could ram a relationship into the ruin but also  transform and beautify the majestic male form.\n\nLong since considered  the  non-plus-ultra of sartorial accessories, the pocket square has been  gracing the upper chests (and awe-stricken eyes) of fashionable men  everywhere from the original Hollywood hunk Clark  Gable to  tailored royalty such as his royal highness the Duke of Windsor. The  hanky donnes the wearer a distinguished air of elegance with perfect  equanimity, and no suit or blazer ensemble dare profess to higher  stratas of gentility sans the tiny cloth. Sadly, the heydays where  elegant men would not be caught dead without the beloved accesory (  Tyrone Power’s wake is a testimanent to this) are progressively being  replaced by a 