(cotton or  foulard work exceptionally well)while thicker looking neckwear should go hand in hand with a silken, or wet garment.\r\n\r\nThe  manifold possibilities of squares and peaks featured in the breast  pockets of past tall, dark and handsomes are a testament of how  individuals give their own personal twist to a long-standing classic.  Cary Grant irregularly angled his to give a little bite to his attire  while Fred Astaire puffed his to complement his entertainment pomp.  Though the thought of folding one’s own handkerchief might send men  scrounging for the hills, this seemingly daunting feat is actually quite  simple to accomplish. The internet provides illustrative guides to the  process while your local dapper dandy is more than willing to guide you  through the ordeal. The magic of folding and placing the handkerchief is  making sure it is not angular and mathematical (since it demonstrates  angularity and constriction). The biggest faux-pas a man could commit  would be to over-emphasize the hanky by making it bulbous and intrusive  for it detracts attention from the face and the attire. When purchasing a  handkerchief, make sure it does not bulge in the pocket (style sage  Alan Flusser suggests a range between 16 and 18 inch. Square).\r\n\r\nThe  handkerchief is not going anywhere as long as men with keen eyes for  reinventing a modern classic continue adapting the tradition into  contemporary times. The hankey adds layers of suaveness and  sophistication to the everyday code and as a true symbol of stylish  “savoir faire” and possesses the ability to transform any  business-formal enslaved man into a true mammal of paradise, which every  male should strive to embody through imagination.','','','inherit','open','open','','134-revision-7','','','2011-03-04 00:39:55','2011-03-04 00:39:55','',134,'http://modernaddendum.com/2011/03/134-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(143,2,'2011-03-04 00:40:46','2011-03-04 00:40:46','In Shakespeare’s “Othello”, our very d