sating with more and more people and even more dances, the alluring veneer of a poorly-patched curtain began bustling with the rustle of musicians setting up. The boys from Macabeo were getting ready, just as the crowd was doing.\r\n\r\nOrquesta El Macabeo is a peculiar cultural phenomenon in the island’s musical scene. Hailing from the mystical lands of Trujillo Alto (and named after one of its fried delicacies), the group has amalgamated members from different backgrounds such as punk and ska, synthesizing a final product which is a no-nonsense hard salsa romper-stomper indebted to the salsa gorda forefathers of the movement. Emphasizing blood, sex, tears and brass instead of the milder, mollified and tamed sound of modern salsa, which tends to the harmlessly romantic, El Macabeo has quickly become a favorite among  young’uns and more “experienced” folk alike for their solid wind arrangements, floor-stomping grooves and un-tinkered sound as seen in their first release “Salsa Macabra”. Not an imitation or copping of past acts, but rather, a reimagining of what salsa should sound like.\r\n\r\nAnd with a flick of a wrist and a pull of a string, the band was unveiled unto the squeezed masses rushed upon the stage. Heating things up with a salsa-funk prelude, the group exploded into the scene, coursing through a string of rambunctious numbers fusing clockwork blowing trumpets, sax and trombone with soaring and gut-kicking vocals. Though the band revels in the jocosity of being wife-whipped in “Supermercado” and the satirical view on unemployment in “Se pone difícil” and chump hustling in “Charlatán”, the orchestra still has time for the socially-relevant discrepancies of modern living in “La Culpa”. Though most material played was from their first release as well as some choice cuts from their up and coming one, the group also revived the salsa classic “El Negro Bembón”, evoking a singing unison from the dancers too tight to move. Though the group cozied up to the frenzy of sweaty rhythms such as their staple “Macabiónico”, El Macabeo proved their chops when they slowed things down a bit with their wounded bolero “La Noche”. Ultra clean and ultra tight melodies, the group blasted walking bass lines, raging timbales and percussion as well as the choral pipes of the front men and tasty organ track.\r\n\r\nThe Macabeo sound had everyone riled up but certainly no one was prepared for the astral slidings of the Zodiac orchestra. Straight out of Loíza in the 1970’s, the stellar sound of the local group became easily identifiable for its darker sounding lyrics and their rawer aesthetic. With groovy records such as “El adios” and “Belleza espiritual vol. 2”, the orchestra has been pressing hot to the touch records ever since, cementing their reputation in the salsa pantheon of the local greats. Kicking off with the title track of the former record, the sing-spoken lament of the jilted lover fills the room with a heavy haze and soon mutates into a swansong croon of pain backed up with a thick and humid rhythm before switching to a fatter number, “Tremendo roblema” which by this time every cretin on the floor started stomping leaving the walls sweatier than the flipside of a frustrated teenager’s hand setting the bases for the primal “El negrito Zabu”.  Not just a full frontal assault, the Zodiac had time to come down as their classic “Mi guitarra”, a melancholic romantic tidbit but surely not for long when the jovial and nature of the band kicked back in with “Belleza espritual”, an honest-to-god ditty about a being paired with a woman with a good heart, even though she’s built like a fridge and a face like a panther.\r\n\r\nIf Macabeo’s set involved tightwound arrangements, Zodiac’s composition tended towards longer and looser interludes. Not old, but “aged” like a good rum that kicks you right between the eyes,  bandleader Paquito Pérez carried the weight around his hips like a moon, and the constant circulation of energy is a testament to it. A gangster, salsa rudeboy, between making jokes and cracking the conducting whip, he points at the crowd, cackles, shoots and blows all of those heads away. The orchestra’s last song, the mournful dirge “Panteón de amor” opened with its own malignant and nefarious sounding organ and took a dive into the mausoleums of heartbreak.\r\n\r\n\"Un Panteón Macabro” was one of those unforgettable cultural experiences were various strata of subcultures converged: with such bodily signs such as tattoos, high heels, floral dresses, 8 inch plugs, guayaberas and fedoras. Zodiac’s last number, with Macabeo singer Luis de la Rosa on chorus, stood as a testament of the passing legacy: a connection between generations united by the love of salsa and the effort and work to keep it alive. Though these two orchestras might not be pushing out radio-friendly singles any time soon, they’re still one of the hardest working acts out there, doing what they want and playing the music the way it should be.','Macabeo and Zodiac meet in stellar slaying: \"Un Panteón Macabro”','Wham bam thank you ma\'m of local salsa mammoths.','publish','open','open','','macabeo-and-zodiac-meet-in-stellar-slaying-un-panteon-macabro%e2%80%9d','','','2011-06-23 20:16:30','2011-06-23 20:16:30','',0,'http://modernaddendum.com/?p=222',0,'post','',0),(223,2,'2011-06-23 20:09:34','2011-06-23 20:09:34','','201436_217506354941903_100000476201617_901079_6216565_o','','inherit','open','open','','201436_217506354941903_100000476201617_901079_6216565_o','','','2011-06-23 20:09:34','2011-06-23 20:09:34','',222,'http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/201436_217506354941903_100000476201617_901079_6216565_o.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(224,2,'2011-06-23 20:07:54','2011-06-23 20:07:54','Saturday night: stranded at the edge of torn posters on Fernandez Juncos Ave. while a gargantuan graffiti whale hovers over my shoulders. What initially seems to be a psychedelic hallucination is in fact the prepostero