fiable for its darker sounding lyrics and their rawer aesthetic. With groovy records such as “El adios” and “Belleza espiritual vol. 2”, the orchestra has been pressing hot to the touch records ever since, cementing their reputation in the salsa pantheon of the local greats. Kicking off with the title track of the former record, the sing-spoken lament of the jilted lover fills the room with a heavy haze and soon mutates into a swansong croon of pain backed up with a thick and humid rhythm before switching to a fatter number, “Tremendo roblema” which by this time every cretin on the floor started stomping leaving the walls sweatier than the flipside of a frustrated teenager’s hand setting the bases for the primal “El negrito Zabu”.  Not just a full frontal assault, the Zodiac had time to come down as their classic “Mi guitarra”, a melancholic romantic tidbit but surely not for long when the jovial and nature of the band kicked back in with “Belleza espritual”, an honest-to-god ditty about a being paired with a woman with a good heart, even though she’s built like a fridge and a face like a panther.\n\nIf Macabeo’s set involved tightwound arrangements, Zodiac’s composition tended towards longer and looser interludes. Not old, but “aged” like a good rum that kicks you right between the eyes,  bandleader Paquito Pérez carried the weight around his hips like a moon, and the constant circulation of energy is a testament to it. A gangster, salsa rudeboy, between making jokes and cracking the conducting whip, he points at the crowd, cackles, shoots and blows all of those heads away. The orchestra’s last song, the mournful dirge “Panteón de amor” opened with its own malignant and nefarious sounding organ and took a dive into the mausoleums of heartbreak.\n\n\"Un Panteón Macabro” was one of those unforgettable cultural experiences were various strata of subcultures converged: with such bodily signs such as tattoos, high heels, floral dresses, 8 inch plugs, guayaberas and fedoras. Zodiac’s last number, with Macabeo singer Luis de la Rosa on chorus, stood as a testament of the passing legacy: a connection between generations united by the love of salsa and the effort and work to keep it alive. Though these two orchestras might not be pushing out radio-friendly singles any time soon, they’re still one of the hardest working acts out there, doing what they want and playing the music the way it should be.','Macabeo and Zodiac meet in stellar slaying: \"Un Panteón Macabro”','Wham bam thank you ma\'m of local salsa mammoths.','inherit','open','open','','222-revision-2','','','2011-06-23 20:15:17','2011-06-23 20:15:17','',222,'http://modernaddendum.com/2011/06/222-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(226,2,'2011-06-23 20:15:52','2011-06-23 20:15:52','Saturday night: stranded at the edge of torn posters on Fernandez Juncos Ave. while a gargantuan graffiti whale hovers over my shoulders. What initially seems to be a psychedelic hallucination is in fact the preposterous line stretching out of La Respuesta’s mouth, slowly gorging the throngs of salsa aficionados who crawled out this evening to witness \"Un Panteón Macabro”,  a macabre meeting between the new heralds of old-school salsa  Orquesta El Macabeo and vanguards of yesteryear, the Orquestra Zodiac .\r\n\r\nKnown usually for hosting upscale shows varying from MC battles, local CD releases to death metal gatherings, the Santurce venue pulled out all the stops to provide a different live experience. Not just any old show with a fistful of rock n’ roll groups spazzing out on stage, this was a concert-affair: tickets up front or suffer whipping out a couple of extra bucks at the door. On the inside, a sonic cloud of salsa greats such as twosome Richie Ray and Bobby Cruz, Willie Colón and Ismael Rivera, handsomely provided by soundsystem guru El Duque de Santurce, spinning classic bone-shaking singles on the plates and while the art gallery-cum-dance floor began pulsating with more and more people an