h their latest hip-shaking extravaganza. ','inherit','open','open','','234-revision-7','','','2011-07-06 00:42:13','2011-07-06 00:42:13','',234,'http://modernaddendum.com/2011/07/234-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(255,2,'2011-10-23 18:12:57','2011-10-23 18:12:57','“What’s so funny motherfucker?” was my reaction to it, this miscreant on the mires of stupidity: shit-greased hair, chin beard, jaw gape and pulverized dentures with a grimy fake tooth.. Only fool’s gold fitted for a fool. But is he?  I cannot help but gaze into that maw of his feel as though some far off remnant of my being malingers beneath. Perhaps he laughs at me.\r\n\r\nUnsettling in characteristic Campo-Formio spiel, the boys’ latest production, <em>Crackman</em>, pummels as hard as a drunken husband. Recorded at “El Dorado” studio by past mixer/masterizer Hector “Stone Tape” Hernández and Los Vigilantes’ own Jorge Mundo, the aural slop comes in a tasty 7” crack-white paste encased by a grinning schizoid fuck-up courtesy of dedicated draftsman Marcos Pechio.\r\n\r\nWith a flick of a pick, the record opens with its six-plus minutes hunkering title-track about a maladjusted motherfucker. With its various strange rooms, the song moves between jagged and ghastly surf runs, maniacal troglodyte stomps and a surplus of brutish riffing. The B-side features a trio of short cuts, starting with “Hoy,” a track that sports a harsh but oddly dreamy intro and machine gun plucking. While “Gen 1” is ostensibly imagined as the airwave friendly single, the wounded croons by moonlight reveal a dormant brutality that swells up and combusts right in your face only to smooth its skirt after losing its cool.  The ghoulish and garagey  “Paco Pepe” swivels between sludgy trudges through fuzz and Sabbath-esque licks all coalesced by its convulsive spouts of anthemic shouts. Shorter than past releases, (the record clocking in at nearly 13 minutes),  the downloadable “Lord of Obstacle” slugs its shoegaze pedals to the max with a panning echo as well as introducing the recognizable Casio keyboard back into the fray, balancing running time.\r\n\r\nJust by looking at the A/B divide, you get what the band’s structural agenda is about: on one side you have sprawling conglomerates of phrases and on the other you have a series of spitfire burst. As much as I get off on the searing face-peeling plunder of the band’s sound, the frenzied riffing of the instrumental passages comes off as distracting from some fascinating moments such as the verses in “Crackman” with its desperate agony and its melancholic droning coda as well as “Gen 1”’s heartwrenching plight. All of the tracks have vocals and lyrics (with the exception of “Lord of Obstacles”) which harkens back to their first releases as well as promising a new sonic body to be explored and experimented with. The disjointed lyrics and vocals are genuinely interesting, more inventive whilst remaining true to their snarling spunk.\r\n\r\nSonically, the album feels full and rounded and is definitely the best sounding production of the catalog. The reverb lies densely layered between the crevices of vinyl grooves, framing a wider and more enveloping listen. As always the group works at a hyperbolic and rigorous metronome, achieving a clockwork antiphony: Diego Bernal’s toms bounce with crisp vibrancy while Fernando Quintero’s fretwork either fumes with grain or chimes with bell-like jangle and Ricardo Perez’s bass is injected with a higher-dosage of mid-gain, drawing attention to the dichotomized melodic duties into twin riffing. Vocals ring wonderfully, particularly in “Gen 1” and its duet with Fernando Samalot of Tach. Dé fame, which provides a sufficiently agonic experience.  The characteristic thrashing interludes are unmuddied and defined, with the particularly punishing guitar tone untouched, while less raucous instances are controlled and taut thanks to curator/mixer/masterizer Hector “Stone Tape” Hernández (whose hodgepodge remix “Amor Borbonico,” included in the download, is a trippy Deerhunter-esque percolating dream sequence.)\r\n\r\nIf <em>Spooky Fools</em> was codified by enigmatic afflictions, <em>Crackman</em> is permeated by a steady sense of utter disgust. Crackman, yet another lanky figure to the Campo-Formio mythos, has just run out of luck and such an epiphany only a vortex of self-hatred re-routed towards others. The album’s scope demonstrates the volatility of violence boiling beneath human remains, sometimes a bit too horrific and alienating to understand how human anyone could relate as “Gen 1”denies the biological lineages and linkages because of the fetid blood. As civilized as humans can feign to be, there is always something intolerably barbaric and there is something even more barbaric in the gaze itself.\r\n\r\nDownload “Lord of Obstacles” and check out more Campo-Formio related stuff at campoformio.bandcamp.com','The Cackle and the Fury: Campo-Formio\'s \"Crackman.\"','The latest sonic slop from these feral kids bends on a darker note.','publish','open','open','','the-cackle-and-the-fury-campo-formios-crackman','','','2011-10-23 18:12:57','2011-10-23 18:12:57','',0,'http://modernaddendum.com/?p=255',0,'post','',0),(246,2,'2011-08-12 16:36:06','2011-08-12 16:36:06','Conclusion is a word usually reserved for historical homes in Maryland, Church synods and science fairs, not  the chaotic, and unending, myriad of human processes in real life but for Los Nervios, the solo project of musician Andrés Fontánez, it time has finally come. With three albums under the proverbial belt and an overall running time of seven-plus years, one of the island’s finer indie pop endeavours is calling it quits for the time being. Gathering influences raging from Euro-electronic groups such as Stereolab to traditional and folkloric island instrumentation, Los Nervios combines the sounds of the future with the infectious forms of the past.\r\n“People would walk up to me and say ‘Man, I want to hear Los Nervios again.’ I’d just say ‘Then put the records on!’ It wasn’t until recently that I considered doing a final show so everyone can have a chance of catching us for one last time” says the bearded masthead of the one man-group.\r\nInterested in the guitar at an early age, but coerced to learn one of the national instruments, the cuatro, by his mother, Fontánez  started getting his kicks and street chops with garage (literally) bands here and there back in the stone age era of dial-up , most notably the electronic ensemble Oscilador 4.  After Fontánez left the band, he found the world of forming a bad quite discouraging: “It’s a hassle: finding a place to practice, finding people, not to mention matching up schedules”. He was eventually recruited by former band mates Jose Olivares, Angelica Negron and Noraliz Ruíz of Oscilador 4 to play guitar for the dreampop outfit, Balún, but since the band was founded in Puerto Rico, yet grounded in New York, Fontánez had a lot of down time and continued writing music on his own until one fine day, a workmate of his at the record store chain “La Gran Discoteca” suggested that he go D.I.Y, bypass any third parties, and commit the songs to tape. It made sense and Los Nervios was born.\r\n2004 saw the release of “EP 1”, a metronome-driven, percolator heavy release full of aqueous fret work and echoing vocals reminiscent of early Galaxy 500-cum-drum machine. With added programming and collaborations from his Balún Tracks gravitate between instrumentals and vocal entendres with groovy cuts such as “No”, a ballad that shifts into a soaring synth-fueled glide while “María, Rosa y Enid”,  a classically-inspired ditty fashioned after folkloric forms, staying true to Fontánez’s musical roots by sporting the use of the cuatro and its counterpart, the tiple.  2007’s follow-up “Puede que hoy sea diferente” was also Los Nervios’ first full-length release which displayed a darker angle in terms of production and sound as well as a more polished, yet rustic, electric soundsphere. “Sobre tú, y yo y todos los que conocemos” styles a more asserted drum beat to a aurally more tense synth pads and “Igual” is indebted to classic Kraftwerk with its poppy digital lead that clashes with “Mejor”, a knife thrust across the veins that sums up the looming isolation given off by the album.\r\nAfter some solo gigging and at the behest of Diego Bernal, current drummer of cretin rockers Campo-Formio but then part of Koala en Krayola and ska ensemble Teodoro y los Neandertales. Reluctant to strike a White Stripes-esque gimmick, Fontánez rounded up a live band consisting of Balun band mates, played a couple of live shows <a href=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/nervios.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-249\" title=\"nervios\" src=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/nervios-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /></a>wherein Ezequiel Rodríguez, of the UPR- radio rock show “Frecuencias Alternas”, approached him with a tasty cyber-project wherein the group would record live music in the studio, à la “Peel Sessions”, for a website. The project collapse, the Balún members split, but Los Nervios dared on and recorded new songs with new members Alexis Reivera Falú   and José Navarro of Don Segundo on keys and bass respectively, took them to Monopolio Records, finished and polished some raw cuts and brought to light 2010’s “La Lombriz”.\r\nArguably the best album in the catalog, the division of musical labors between members old and new achieves a more eclectic sonic palette combining elements from ska, reggae, new wave and electronic music such as “Distinto” an echoing skanky number with floating synths and “Eloise”, a bossa nova groove while “El Miedo” is a an upbeat ska single unafraid to shake off stage-freight. Not only is the album aurally diverse but lyrically more introspective as is the fan favorite title track, thanks to Fontánez’s partner Lizthayra Carreras González’s input:  “She showed me all of these poems she wrote about a bad breakup and I thought they were great, so I just wrote the music to the words.” The varied input moves the overall feel from simple contributions that add color to a more organic, fluid and pulsating listening experience, not just in style, but more importantly in substance.\r\nLos Nervios’ music demonstrates a shattering loneliness of, not only of the quotidian and the begrudged content but of the creative process. The difficulties of communication and somewhat vacuous nature of dealing with a routine abound, but the common thread between all the releases is a ingrained sense of lingering melancholy that occasionally surfaces but further into the grain, there is an obfuscated optimism. The fear of loss as well as the nervousness (as is the namesake) when faced with life eventually give way to discovery and reconnection. Where there is an obstacle, it is not a precedent of an abyss of solitude, but an opportunity.\r\nLos Nervios is one of those groups from a particular time with a particular sound: where most groups were still awashed with the post Rock en Espanol craze, Fontanez opted for the more unconventional and the challenging, especially in a place where equipment and electronic composition is untrodden territory much like other local talents such as Superaquello have ventured to.  With such an ample sonic reach and a super-tight full band, one can only hope a great happening like Los Nervios is not saying goodbye, but, rather, until next time.\r\nLos Nervios will be playing their final show Saturday night, at Abracadabra on the Juan Ponce de Leon Ave, Santurce alongside The Bee’s Knee’s and Campo-Formio with DJ sets by Chasm-Filler. You can download Los Nervios’ complete discography for free at <a href=\"www.losnervios.bandcamp.com.\">www.losnervios.bandcamp.com.</a>','Struck a nerve: A look at Los Nervios','With three albums and a running time clocking in at seven plus years, Los Nervios play their last show.','publish','open','open','','struck-a-nerve-a-look-at-los-nervios','','','2011-08-12 16:37:51','2011-08-12 16:37:51','',0,'http://modernaddendum.com/?p=246',0,'post','',0),(247,2,'2011-08-12 16:25:24','2011-08-12 16:25:24','Conclusion is a word usually reserved for historical homes in Maryland, Church synods and science fairs, not  the chaotic, and unending, myriad of human processes in real life but for Los Nervios, the solo project of musician Andrés Fontánez, it time has finally come. With three albums under the proverbial belt and an overall running time of seven-plus years, one of the island’s finer indie pop endeavours is calling it quits for the time being. Gathering influences raging from Euro-electronic groups such as Stereolab to traditional and folkloric island instrumentation, Los Nervios combines the sounds of the future with the infectious forms of the past.\n“People would walk up to me and say ‘Man, I want to hear Los Nervios again.’ I’d just say ‘Then put the records on!’ It wasn’t until recently that I considered doing a final show so everyone can have a chance of catching us for one last time” says the bearded masthead of the one man-group.  \nInterested in the guitar at an early age, but coerced to learn one of the national instruments, the cuatro, by his mother, Fontánez  started getting his kicks and street chops with garage (literally) bands here and there back in the stone age era of dial-up , most notably the electronic ensemble Oscilador 4.  After Fontánez left the band, he found the world of forming a bad quite discouraging: “It’s a hassle: finding a place to practice, finding people, not to mention matching up schedules”. He was eventually recruited by former band mates Jose Olivares, Angelica Negron and Noraliz Ruíz of Oscilador 4 to play guitar for the dreampop outfit, Balún, but since the band was founded in Puerto Rico, yet grounded in New York, Fontánez had a lot of down time and continued writing music