z’s input:  “She showed me all of these poems she wrote about a bad breakup and I thought they were great, so I just wrote the music to the words.” The varied input moves the overall feel from simple contributions that add color to a more organic, fluid and pulsating listening experience, not just in style, but more importantly in substance.\r\nLos Nervios’ music demonstrates a shattering loneliness of, not only of the quotidian and the begrudged content but of the creative process. The difficulties of communication and somewhat vacuous nature of dealing with a routine abound, but the common thread between all the releases is a ingrained sense of lingering melancholy that occasionally surfaces but further into the grain, there is an obfuscated optimism. The fear of loss as well as the nervousness (as is the namesake) when faced with life eventually give way to discovery and reconnection. Where there is an obstacle, it is not a precedent of an abyss of solitude, but an opportunity.\r\nLos Nervios is one of those groups from a particular time with a particular sound: where most groups were still awashed with the post Rock en Espanol craze, Fontanez opted for the more unconventional and the challenging, especially in a place where equipment and electronic composition is untrodden territory much like other local talents such as Superaquello have ventured to.  With such an ample sonic reach and a super-tight full band, one can only hope a great happening like Los Nervios is not saying goodbye, but, rather, until next time.\r\nLos Nervios will be playing their final show Saturday night, at Abracadabra on the Juan Ponce de Leon Ave, Santurce alongside The Bee’s Knee’s and Campo-Formio with DJ sets by Chasm-Filler. You can download Los Nervios’ complete discography for free at www.losnervios.bandcamp.com.','Struck a nerve: A look at Los Nervios','With three albums and a running time clocking in at seven plus years, Los Nervios play their last show.','inherit','open','open','','246-revision-4','','','2011-08-12 16:36:06','2011-08-12 16:36:06','',246,'http://modernaddendum.com/2011/08/246-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(256,2,'2011-10-23 18:07:39','2011-10-23 18:07:39','“What’s so funny motherfucker?” was my reaction to it, this miscreant on the mires of stupidity: shit-greased hair, chin beard, jaw gape and pulverized dentures with a grimy fake tooth.. Only fool’s gold fitted for a fool. But is he?  I cannot help but gaze into that maw of his feel as though some far off remnant of my being malingers beneath. Perhaps he laughs at me.\n\nUnsettling in characteristic Campo-Formio spiel, the boys’ latest production, <em>Crackman</em>, pummels as hard as a drunken husband. Recorded at “El Dorado” studio by past mixer/masterizer Hector “Stone Tape” Hernández and Los Vigilantes’ own Jorge Mundo, the aural slop comes in a tasty 7” crack-white paste encased by a grinning schizoid fuck-up courtesy of dedicated draftsman Marcos Pechio.\n\nWith a flick of a pick, the record opens with its six-plus minutes hunkering title-track about a maladjusted motherfucker. With its various strange rooms, the song moves between jagged and ghastly surf runs, maniacal troglodyte stomps and a surplus of brutish riffing. The B-side features a trio of short cuts, starting with “Hoy,” a track that sports a harsh but oddly dreamy intro and machine gun plucking. While “Gen 1” is ostensibly imagined as the airwave friendly single, the wounded croons by moonlight reveal a dormant brutality that swells up and combusts right in your face only to smooth its skirt after losing its cool.  The ghoulish and garagey  “Paco Pepe” swivels between sludgy trudges through fuzz and Sabbath-esque licks all coalesced by its convulsive spouts of anthemic shouts. Shorter than past releases, (the record clocking in at nearly 13 minutes),  the downloadable “Lord of Obstacle” slugs its shoegaze pedals to the max with a panning echo as well as introducing the recognizable Casio keyboard back into the fray, balancing running time.\n\nJust by looking at the A/B divide, you get what the band’s structural agenda is about: on one side you have sprawling conglomerates of phrases and on the other you have a series of spitfire burst. As much as I get off on the searing face-peeling plunder of the band’s sound, the frenzied riffing of the instrumental passages comes off as distracting from some fascinating moments such as the verses in “Crackman” with its desperate agony and its melancholic droning coda as well as “Gen 1”’s heartwrenching plight. All of the tracks have vocals and lyrics (with the exception of “Lord of Obstacles”) which harkens back to their first releases as well as promising a new sonic body to be explored and experimented with. The disjointed lyrics and vocals are genuinely interesting, more inventive whilst remaining true to their snarling spunk.\n\nSonically, the album feels full and rounded and is definitely the best sounding production of the catalog. The reverb lies densely layered between the crevices of vinyl grooves, framing a wider and more enveloping listen. As always the group works at a hyperbolic and rigorous metronome, achieving a clockwork antiphony: Diego Bernal’s toms bounce with crisp vibrancy while Fernando Quintero’s fretwork either fumes with grain or chimes with bell-like jangle and Ricardo Perez’s bass is injected with a higher-dosage of mid-gain, drawing attention to the dichotomized melodic duties into twin riffing. Vocals ring wonderfully, particularly in “Gen 1” and its duet with Fernando Samalot of Tach. Dé fame, which provides a sufficiently agonic experience.  The characteristic thrashing interludes are unmuddied and defined, with the particularly punishing guitar tone untouched, while less raucous instances are controlled and taut thanks to curator/mixer/masterizer Hector “Stone Tape” Hernández (whose hodgepodge remix “Amor Borbonico,” included in the download, is a trippy Deerhunter-esque percolating dream sequence.)\n\nIf <em>Spooky Fools</em> was codified by enigmatic afflictions, <em>Crackman</em> is permeated by a steady sense of utter disgust. Crackman, yet another lanky figure to the Campo-Formio mythos, has just run out of luck and such an epiphany only a vortex of self-hatred re-routed towards others. The album’s scope demonstrates the volatility of violence boiling beneath human remains, sometimes a bit too horrific and alienating to understand how human anyone could relate as “Gen 1”denies the biological lineages and linkages because of the fetid blood. As civilized as humans can feign to be, there is always something intolerably barbaric and there is something even more barbaric in the gaze itself.\n\nDownload “Lord of Obstacles” and check out more Campo-Formio related stuff at campoformio.bandcamp.com','The Cackle and the Fury: Campo-Formio\'s \"Crackman.\"','','inherit','open','open','','255-revision','','','2011-10-23 18:07:39','2011-10-23 18:07:39','',255,'http://modernaddendum.com/2011/10/255-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(257,2,'2011-10-23 18:12:33','2011-10-23 18:12:33','','crackman1','','inherit','open','open','','crackman1','','','2011-10-23 18:12:33','2011-10-23 18:12:33','',255,'http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/crackman1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(258,2,'2011-10-23 18:12:09','2011-10-23 18:12:09','“What’s so funny motherfucker?” was my reaction to it, this miscreant on the mires of stupidity: shit-greased hair, chin beard, jaw gape and pulverized dentures with a grimy fake tooth.. Only fool’s gold fitted for a fool. But is he?  I cannot help but gaze into that maw of his feel as though some far off remnant of my being malingers beneath. Perhaps he laughs at me.\r\n\r\nUnsettling in characteristic Campo-Formio spiel, the boys’ latest production, <em>Crackman</em>, pummels as hard as a drunken husband. Recorded at “El Dorado” studio by past mixer/masterizer Hector “Stone Tape” Hernández and Los Vigilantes’ own Jorge Mundo,