apse into the arpeggiated intro of “I Be Making Thoughts,” a down-and-out driving kicker that soon takes a wrong turn at dirtyville with “Rag Doll,” a sloppy floor stomper with moronic chorites and some caustic fuzz guitar guaranteed to have you quaffing tall cool ones all night.\r\n\r\nWith such a tight knit double whoppers headlining the album, the middle cluster of songs is kind of a disappointing foray, starting with “Blessing In Desguise” (grammar is clearly not it), a upbeat ditty that never quite comes, but slips out of a dull Gordian knot with an interesting and blistering anthemic passage while “Try It!” tries to be a heavy-hitting track but comes off a bit mild ,but it’s saving grace lies in its brief mid-song kickshift riff-o-rama. Though“Convictions” is an angsty progression punctuated by bass thumps and cohesive push/pull rhythms, a welcome breath of stasis while “Young Days” feels like a loosely stringed collage of riffs.\r\n\r\nFortunately, the tailing cluster of songs vindicates and more than makes up for its previous efforts with “Party Everyday,” a mesmerizing, and poignant,  piece that locks into a jangly groove with enigmatic and ethereal voices permeating the cut while “Shut Down,” starts out as a lofty ballad before reverting into a massive downtroke wall of distortion. Carried on the heaves of brutal drumming, the track perfectly balances shimmering pop-sensibilities and aggressive grit, glossed over with palpable uneasiness and dissonant chord strums.  Clearly the crowning piece in the album, it comes off as you might have heard of before, but all together alien with its phasing swaths of electric goodness, one of those rare tracks of color and form that stick around much more than it’s supposed to.\r\n\r\nSonically consonant with an array of 90’s heyday “indie” bands as well as name-checking canonical noisesmiths Sonic Yourth, the record injec. The production, overseered by Ruy Andres, chimes: he metallic bass jangle and high-end fretwork are grounded with tightwind percussions. The programmed melodies flavors and ties together the other melodies, moving into unexplored electronic terrain without being to heavy-handed on lame synths. Vocals sometimes delve into out-of key barely tolerable chicanery but tracks like “Party Everyday” and “Shut Down” sport intonated singing with a steady focus.\r\n\r\nThe EP is summed up in a miniscule anthology of hits and misses. The misses demonstrate a struggle for control over direction, clunky because it sounds pieced, transparent,  perhaps seeking to infuse sentiment but end up wallowing in yelping sentimentalism, but when they’re not complaining about not fucking girls (yuck!), the hits feel authentic and new: the disparate voices coalesce, sounds become woven, the snark hits your chest like a fistful of hammers.\r\n\r\nThough The Bee’s Knees are not quite the cat’s pajamas with the EP, they are well on their way at paving they’re own aural mishaps, but perhaps they’re music reveals much more than it does at face value. The fractured and urgent sentiment and production should not be confused with amateurism, but with still-teenage pangs. The music captures opaque, yet jem-like gut feeling of putting it something out there. Youth is wasted on the young, and as such getting wasted at elaborating something concrete out of something ephemeral transcends the tyranny of utter boredom. Seeing these cats playing in different band (perennial babyfaced Cristian Zayas in Naranja and the mustachioed Ivan Moreira in Codex), brings to mind continual process, a steady fluxus between bodies. Though many, borne away like salt into the sea, disappear, other regenerate, other come to table gear head lingo and acryclic jargon at will. There are no circles, no drafted parameters, the only subculture there is of youth: irresponsible  And that edge-of-the-seat feeling, that impending something that seems to cut through every sonic artefact some one in this island puts out, is out there. The youth, the artist, miscreant, cretin, ne’er-do-well is uneasy, because they are waiting for something. They know it will happen. Things are happening all the time, but not the big one. Not yet the heavy star everyone slouches and works towards to. They know something will happen. They just don’t know how.','Wasted Youth: The Bee\'s Knees\' First EP','','publish','open','open','','wasted-youth-the-bees-knees-first-ep','','','2011-12-16 17:25:00','2011-12-16 17:25:00','',0,'http://modernaddendum.com/?p=260',0,'post','',0),(261,2,'2011-12-16 17:10:47','2011-12-16 17:10:47','The cover is an allotment of dreamy photographs plastered on a pale wall: a candelabra lighting an enormous room, castles unheard, phantom self-portraits, fat dogs; memories of things that might not have happened, the back of the record is the ghosts of three glassy-eyed motherfuckers. One side intimate, the other irreverent. This is the breaching sentiment, or at least what was aimed at, in The Bee’s Knees’ freshman EP debut. Coming in a classy CD-R honey-yellow veneer, the disc has a little bit for everyone, and a little bit that’s not.\n\nA percolating pulse preludes a flurry of wounded guitar noise and fluttering analog bleeps before the sonic walls collapse into the arpeggiated intro of “I Be Making Thoughts,” a down-and-out driving kicker that soon takes a wrong turn at dirtyville with “Rag Doll,” a sloppy floor stomper with moronic chorites and some caustic fuzz guitar guaranteed to have you quaffing tall cool ones all night.\n\nWith such a tight knit double whoppers headlining the album, the middle cluster of songs is kind of a disappointing foray, starting with “Blessing In Desguise” (grammar is clearly not it), a upbeat ditty that never quite comes, but slips out of a dull Gordian knot with an interesting and blistering anthemic passage while “Try It!” tries to be a heavy-hitting track but comes off a bit mild ,but it’s saving grace lies in its brief mid-song kickshift riff-o-rama. Tho