elstrom, to maintain this state of awareness. Perhaps painting and poetry only reveal what is implicit: that these concepts, ideas and correspondences are but introductions, not resolutions, a sort of prelude to our grand awakening. But this sensual apprehension is not selfish, for it demands a physical manifestation of itself for others to witness the same visions of ecstasy. Thus the continuum flows; the experience of art is not as obscure as the heavens, but all too real. We always carry in us that moment on immemorial beauty when we encounter art, and all other creations are but interpretations of that moment. Rossetti has made the dirge resound through the painting and I can only wring a broken madrigal through this text.','The Roman Widow ','','inherit','open','open','','301-revision-6','','','2013-05-07 20:06:17','2013-05-07 20:06:17','',301,'http://modernaddendum.com/2013/05/301-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(310,2,'2013-05-07 20:06:59','2013-05-07 20:06:59','The following essay is the final chapter of my M.A. thesis <em>Ut Pictura Poesis: Dante Gabriel Rossetti and the Double Work of Art. </em>While technically a conclusion, I believe it still works as a critical introduction to his double work of art while elucidating some aspects of the historical context and social world view of Victorian art and literature culture during Rossetti\'s active years.\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 120px;\">Picture and poem bare the same relation to each other as beauty does in man and woman: the point of meeting where the two are most identical is the supreme perfection.\r\n-Dante Gabriel Rossetti, <i>Sentences and Notes</i></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 120px;\">That he had this gift of transparency in language—the control of a style which did but obediently shift and shape itself to the mental motion, as a well-trained hand can follow on the tracing-paper the outline of an original drawing below it.\r\n-Walter Pater, “Dante Gabriel Rossetti,” <i>Appreciations</i></p>\r\n